  "prompt": "How can I avoid getting zits above my lip?",
  "response": "To help prevent zits above your lip, consider following these tips:\n\n1. **Maintain Good Hygiene**: Regularly wash your face with a gentle cleanser, especially after sweating or wearing makeup. Avoid harsh scrubs that can irritate the skin.\n\n2. **Avoid Touching Your Face**: Your hands can transfer oils and bacteria to your skin, so try to avoid resting your face in your hands or touching it frequently.\n\n3. **Keep Your Lips Hydrated**: Use a lip balm to avoid chapped lips, which can lead to irritation and breakouts.\n\n4. **Be Cautious with Hair Products**: Hair gels, sprays, and oils can transfer to the skin above your lip, potentially clogging pores. Choose products that are non-comedogenic, which means they won't contribute to acne.\n\n5. **Watch Your Diet**: Some people find that certain foods can trigger breakouts. Pay attention to your diet and note any foods that seem to correlate with breakouts above your lip.\n\n6. **Use Non-Comedogenic Makeup**: If you wear makeup, opt for products labeled as non-comedogenic to minimize the risk of clogged pores.\n\n7. **Exfoliate Regularly**: Gentle exfoliation can help remove dead skin cells that clog pores, but be careful not to overdo it, as this can irritate your skin and worsen the problem.\n\n8. **Manage Stress**: Stress can lead to hormonal changes that may cause breakouts. Engage in stress-reducing activities like exercise, yoga, or meditation.\n\n9. **Consult a Dermatologist**: If breakouts persist, consider talking to a dermatologist. They can provide tailored advice and recommend appropriate treatments, which may include topical creams or medications.\n\n10. **Be Mindful of Hormonal Fluctuations**: If you notice a pattern with breakouts, it may be related to your menstrual cycle. Keeping track of this may help you manage potential breakouts.\n\nRemember that everyone's skin is different, so it may take some experimentation to find what works best for you.",
